<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-04-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-04-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="649" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d649">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Dudley</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-04-11"><hi rend="italic">April 11,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 325.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            No. 879, of the 5th ultimo, reporting that you had pointed out to the
                            Peruvian minister of foreign relations the inability of the United
                            States legation and consulates to give the certificate required by a
                            recent supreme decree, providing that foreigners desiring to marry in
                            Peru must furnish a certificate of celibacy from their legation or
                            consulate.</p>
                        <p>The views expressed by you are correct and are approved by the
                            Department.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>